definition.value: A disaccharide having rhamnose at the reducing end with a glycosyl residue attached at an unspecified position via a glycosidic bond.
A beta-D-glucoside having a malonyl group at the 6-position and a 3-O-delphinidin moiety at the anomeric position.
An anthocyanin cation consisting of delphinidin with beta-D-glucosyl groups at the 3-, 3'- and 5'-positions.
An anthocyanin cation consisting of delphinidin with beta-D-glucosyl groups at the 3- and 3'-positions.
A polyprenol diphosphate of unspecified chain-length with all double bonds having (E)-configuration.
A diblock copolymer composed of adjacent blocks of polystyrene and poly(2-vinylpyridine).
Any salt of camphorsulfonic acid.
The hydrochloride salt of morphine.
The ester formed between N-hydroxysuccinimide and (4-hydroxy-3-nitrophenyl)acetic acid.
The ester formed between N-hydroxysuccinimide and (4-hydroxy-5-iodo-3-nitrophenyl)acetic acid.
A nitrite ester having n-pentyl as the alkyl group.
The hydrochloride salt of anagrelide.
A semisynthetic echinocandin anti-fungal drug. It is active against Aspergillus and Candida species and is used for the treatment of invasive candidiasis.
A class of anticoagulants which act by inhibiting the action of vitamin K.
A parenteral third-generation cephalosporin, bearing a 2-(2-amino-1,3-thiazol-4-yl)-2-(methoxyimino)acetyl]amino group at the 7beta-position.
The trihydrate of morphine hydrochloride.
A germacranolide derived from laurenobiolide by deacetylation.
An antagonist at the neurokinin-1 receptor.
An antagonist at the substance P receptor.
The (R)-enantiomer of atenolol.
A tricarboxylic acid compound consisting of but-2-ene having carboxy substituents at the 1-, 2- and 3-positions.
A tryptophan derivative having a chloro substituent at the 7-position of the indole ring.
The chloride salt of ipratropium.
A 7-chlorotryptophan in which the chiral centre has D- (R-) configuration.
A piperazine-2-carboxamide having (R)-configuration.
A piperazine-2-carboxylic acid having (R)-configuration.
Conjugate base of (R)-piperazine-2-carboxylic acid.
An N-tert-butyl substituted piperazine-2-carboxamide having (R)-configuration.
An amino acid amide compound consisting of propionamide having a 3-amino substituent.
A germacranolide isolated from Laurus nobilis L.
The (R)-enantiomer of azelastine.
The (S)-enantiomer of azelastine.
The aromatic diazonium ion corresponding to (p-aminophenyl)arsonic acid (arsanilic acid).
A member of the class of  cinnamaldehydes carrying a hexyl substituent at the alpha-position.

A nucleotide residue consisting of a nucleobase bound at the glycosidic nitrogen to a ribose ring that has a free valence at an oxygen atom and which is bound at the O-5' atom to a phosphate group, having a further free valence at one of its oxygen atoms.

A nucleotide residue consisting of a nucleobase bound at the glycosidic nitrogen to a 2'-deoxyribose ring that has a free valence at an oxygen atom and which is bound at the O-5' atom to a phosphate group, having a further free valence at one of its oxygen atoms.
The hydrochloride salt of mechlorethamine.
Compounds containing an ifosfamide skeleton.

A monocarboxylic acid amide resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of 1-methyl-1H-indazole-3-carboxylic acid with the primary amino group of (3-endo)-9-methyl-9-azabicyclo[3.3.1]nonan-3-amine. A selective 5-HT3 receptor antagonist, it is used (generally as the monohydrochloride salt) to manage nausea and vomiting caused by cancer chemotherapy and radiotherapy, and to prevent and treat postoperative nausea and vomiting.
An imidazolidine containing one or more oxo groups.
An isoquinoline containing one or more oxo groups.
A 2-benzofuran containing one or more oxo groups.
Oxazoles in which the N and O atoms are adjacent.
An oxazolidine containing one or more oxo groups.
An oxazolidinone in which the N and O atoms are adjacent.
Ferriheme b carrying an overall charge of -1, caused by loss of a proton from each of the two carboxy groups.
A dimer of hematin in which an iron-oxygen bond links the central iron of one hematin to the oxygen of one of the carboxylates of the adjacent hematin.
